metadata.definition: In general, the unemployed population is considered, that is, both unemployed people who are unemployed who have previously had a job and those who are seeking work for the first time. The data correspond to the open unemployment and urban coverage unless it is indicated that it is hidden unemployment and / or national coverage. In the case of urban coverage, this can refer to the total of urban areas, according to the definition of the corresponding country, or to a group of cities or metropolitan areas. The years between countries also vary because the figures come from official national sources of the countries.
metadata.calculation_methodology: Percentage of unemployed population in relation to the economically active population. Information comes from national official sources. The regional total was estimated as an average using figures on the population of working age according to the projections elaborated by CELADE.
metadata.comments:
Unemployment rates by country come from official sources of each of the countries, are compiled by the Economic Development Division and are used by ECLAC in its main economic publications. The data refer to "open" unemployment rates, unless a note indicates that "hidden" unemployment is included.

To the users of this indicator, it is recommended to keep in mind the content of the calls regarding the temporal and regional coverage within each of the countries. For the regional aggregate, depending on the number of countries incorporated in the calculation and only for purposes of comparability, two periods are distinguished. The first covers the period 1981-1990 and includes 16 countries, namely: Argentina, Bolivia, Brazil, Chile, Colombia, Costa Rica, Ecuador, Guatemala, Honduras, Mexico, Nicaragua, Panama, Paraguay, Peru, Uruguay and Venezuela. , while for the second period the regional average shows data since 1991/92 and includes, in addition to the 16 countries already mentioned, the Bahamas, Barbados, Belize, Cuba, El Salvador, Jamaica, the Dominican Republic and Trinidad and Tobago.

In some countries and years for which official data are not available, regional data incorporate own estimates. Due to its non-official nature, these data are not available in this database.
